1
01:00:00,166 --> 01:00:02,533
<b>Ever heard somebody say that Ukrainian is</b>

2
01:00:02,533 --> 01:00:04,033
<b>just Russian with an accent?</b>

3
01:00:04,466 --> 01:00:06,766
<b>Russia tried banning Ukrainian twice.</b>

4
01:00:07,166 --> 01:00:10,033
<b>In 1863 a Russian minister declared</b>

5
01:00:10,033 --> 01:00:13,433
<b>Ukrainian to be "not real", just a</b>

6
01:00:13,433 --> 01:00:14,933
<b>twisted version of Russian.</b>

7
01:00:15,566 --> 01:00:17,733
<b>Then in 1876 Tsar</b>

8
01:00:17,733 --> 01:00:19,866
<b>Alexander II made it worse.</b>

9
01:00:20,533 --> 01:00:22,699
<b>Ukrainian was banned in books, in</b>

10
01:00:22,699 --> 01:00:25,000
<b>schools, in place, in education.</b>

11
01:00:25,466 --> 01:00:27,300
<b>These weren't small rules, this was</b>

12
01:00:27,300 --> 01:00:28,833
<b>full-on language erasure.</b>

13
01:00:29,300 --> 01:00:31,666
<b>Schools were silenced, churches were</b>

14
01:00:31,666 --> 01:00:33,833
<b>closed, printing was outlawed.</b>

15
01:00:34,233 --> 01:00:35,533
<b>But Ukraine didn't give in.</b>

16
01:00:36,066 --> 01:00:38,733
<b>Secret schools, exile presses and</b>

17
01:00:38,733 --> 01:00:40,633
<b>families whispering Ukrainian</b>

18
01:00:40,633 --> 01:00:42,566
<b>poems kept the language alive.</b>

19
01:00:42,800 --> 01:00:45,633
<b>Today some call Ukraine "little Russian"</b>

20
01:00:45,833 --> 01:00:48,333
<b>or "Novorossiya" "new Russia".</b>

21
01:00:48,533 --> 01:00:51,233
<b>But when a culture not only survives two</b>

22
01:00:51,233 --> 01:00:53,966
<b>bans and centuries of repression,</b>

23
01:00:54,266 --> 01:00:56,866
<b>it is not just fake, it is resilient.</b>

